    "summary": "The Fifth Dynasty of Egypt, roughly 2494–2345 BC, followed the extraordinary pyramid-building era of the Fourth Dynasty and is characterised by a gradual redistribution of royal power toward a broader elite, growing importance of the sun-cult at Heliopolis, and the construction of solar temples alongside the royal pyramids. While the pyramids of Fifth Dynasty pharaohs are smaller and less well-preserved than those of the Fourth Dynasty, the period is notable for important religious and literary developments.\n\nUnder Fifth Dynasty rulers such as Userkaf, Sahure, and Unas, the solar deity Ra achieved dominance in the Egyptian state religion. Each king constructed not only a pyramid but also a dedicated solar temple, typically featuring a large obelisk on a raised platform as a focal point for sun worship. This shift reflects the growing influence of the priesthood of Ra at Heliopolis and a theological evolution toward a more solar-centred cosmology.\n\nThe most significant cultural legacy of the Fifth Dynasty is the composition of the [[event:1716|Pyramid Texts]], first inscribed in the burial chambers of Pharaoh Unas, the last ruler of the dynasty. These religious spells and hymns, intended to guide and protect the deceased pharaoh in the afterlife, are the oldest known corpus of religious texts from ancient Egypt. They represent the beginning of a long tradition of Egyptian funerary literature and provide invaluable insight into Old Kingdom theology and cosmology.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fifth_Dynasty_of_Egypt",
